 Nation at a Glance

 Indian immigrant shot dead in NY

 new york (PTI): In a botched robbery attempt, a masked bandit shot dead an immigrant from India who was working as a cashier in a bakery. 

 George Kuruvilla, 52, was shot dead in the shop where he had been working for the last 15 years. Nothing was stolen from the store.

 The bandit burst into the bakery in Queens, a suburb of New York City, on Saturday around 6 pm local time and shot Kuruvilla in the head. 

 As he lay dying, other employees of the bakery ran out screaming and took shelter in neighbouring houses. 

 Kuruvilla leaves behind his wife Saramma and 17-year-old daughter Nimmy. 

 Laloo, Mishra in scam denial

 Ranchi: Two former chief ministers of Bihar on Monday pleaded not guilty to the charge of conspiring against the state to siphon off Rs 182.82 crore from the Doranda treasury between 1988 and 1996, and Rs 96 lakh from the Deoghar treasury between 1991 and 1994, reports our bureau.

 Both Laloo Prasad Yadav, the railway minister, and Dr Jagannath Mishra appeared before two special CBI courts, where the fodder-scam accused are being prosecuted. 

 In the first case they are being tried along with 148 other people while in the second case, they are the co-accused with 26 other people. With the framing of charges on Monday, the trial in both the cases has formally begun.

 Cabbie relief

 new delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court has ordered a compensation of Rs 2 lakh to a taxi driver, who was allegedly shot at by a policeman here last year. 

 Surender Singh alleged that Anoop Singh had stopped him at Najafgarh while he was travelling by the Bahadurgarh-Nangloi inter-state link road and demanded Rs 2,000 as entry fee. Surender said the traffic police ASI shot at him thinking he was trying to flee. 

 Cops injured

 jaipur (PTI): At least 100 policemen were injured when a group of businessmen, protesting against the Rajasthan governments decision on contracting farming and trading to private firms, threw stones at them here on Monday. They attacked the police for trying to stop their leaders from marching to the state secretariat. 

 Canal project 

 new delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has issued notices to the Centre and Tamil Nadu government on a petition challenging environmental clearance to the Sethusamudram project. It has sought a reply within four weeks. 

 The number of expatriate workers, including Indians, employed in Oman has fallen by 24.4 per cent in the last three years because of the governments efforts to ensure jobs for citizens.




